	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>FSC reiterates commitment to American Sugars under the Tate &amp; Lyle agreement </h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In October, the executive chairman of the Fiji Sugar Corporation (FSC) reiterated the company’s commitment to ‘fulfilling contractual obligations to American Sugars ... despite strong interest from Queensland Sugar Limited ... in purchasing sugar from FSC’. FSC made a commitment to supplying sugar to American Sugars until 2015 under a 5-year contract concluded with Tate &amp; Lyle prior to the take-over of Tate &amp; Lyle’s sugar divisions by American Sugars (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Tate-and-Lyle-sugar-division-sold-to-US-company" target="_blank">Tate and Lyle sugar division sold to US company</a>’, August 2010).</p><p>Currently FSC looks set to supply 200,000 tonnes of sugar in 2011, up from 131,000 tonnes last year. Government officials talk optimistically of future sugar production reaching 400,000 tonnes, at which point, it is maintained, ‘interest from buyers in the Middle East, China, Japan and Bangladesh’ can be explored.</p><p>At the end of October it was announced that ‘the review of Fiji’s Sugar Industry Act has been completed’. The aim of the review was to ‘streamline the country’s sugar industry’. However no details of the actions to be taken on the basis of the review were forthcoming. According to press reports, the permanent secretary for sugar acknowledged that ‘considering the serious decline the industry had experienced over the past six years, it would be some time before Fiji began to see the positive results of reforms which were currently under way.’</p><p>Press reports referred to allegations of sabotage emanating from the military government and claims from the prime minister that ‘some people in the management had also been part of the problem’, with these politically motivated actions seeking to ‘perpetuate an inefficient system’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Fiji Times</i>, ‘Miller sticks to deals’, 25 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=184121" target="_self">http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=184121</a></p><p><i>Fiji</i><i> Sun</i>, ‘Fiji’s sugar review act completed’, 1 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=17014041014eaf3dae9d14a278c8da" target="_self">http://www.pina.com.fj/index.php?p=pacnews&amp;m=read&amp;o=17014041014e...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>High global prices and weather-related production disruption would appear to account for Queensland Sugar’s current interest in Fijian sugar.&nbsp; The interest of Queensland Sugar and other importers in Fijian sugar may not be so strong come 2015, depending as it will on market conditions and weather-related events. The current situation provides opportunities for mobilising external support, with industry restructuring aimed at repositioning the Fijian sugar industry in the light of evolving trends in the global sugar market.</p><p>However this requires the development of a clear strategic vision of the industry, the identification of strategic partners and the elaboration of realistic financial and operational plans. It is unclear to what extent the current review of the Sugar Industry Act will contribute to this process.</p><p>Operational details linked to the review have yet to be elaborated. How, for example will actions identified in the review be financed? There is already uncertainty on the use of the $100m or so budgeted by government for the industry this year. Moreover, the EU’s aid funds are still suspended and may have been lost already to Fiji.</p><p>While the current focus appears to be on identifying possible buyers of Fijian&nbsp; sugar when output returns to the high levels of the past, what Fiji needs in order to face an uncertain future is the establishment of partnerships with active and resource-endowed global sugar players who can diversify the industry into sustainable new directions.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
